<p>
  managing renewals for one property is already a cognitive load. for landlords with 3, 5, or 10+ properties, it becomes a full-time part of the job — one that almost nobody budgets for and almost everyone gets wrong.
</p>

<h3>the multi-property renewal calendar</h3>

<p>
  a typical landlord with 5 properties might have: 5 buildings insurance policies, 5 landlord insurance policies, 5 gas safety certificates (annual), 5 energy performance certificates (every 5–10 years, but staggered), 5 electrical installation condition reports (every 5 years), plus mortgage deals ending, tenancy renewals, and maintenance contracts.
</p>

<p>
  that's 15–25 renewal events per year, each on a different date, each with different notice periods, each with different renewal processes. none of them synchronise. and the consequences of missing one range from a £200 excess charge to a £5,000 fine for non-compliance.
</p>

<h3>the insurance stealth hike</h3>

<p>
  landlord and buildings insurance for rental properties sees some of the steepest renewal hikes in the insurance market — regularly 20–35% year-on-year. because landlords are classified as commercial customers, they don't benefit from the same fca protections as consumer insurance. the loyalty penalty is uncapped.
</p>

<p>
  for a landlord with 5 properties paying an average of £350/year each, a 25% average renewal hike means £437.50/year extra — across all properties, that's £1,750/year in loyalty penalties before you've done anything about it.
</p>

<h3>how perch. helps</h3>

<p>
  forward all renewal notices to a single @perch.app address. perch. tags each item by property and category, gives you a calendar view of everything renewing across your portfolio, and flags the worst offenders. the weekly digest tells you which properties need attention this week — no spreadsheets, no missed deadlines.
</p>
